{"id":"d=origam-topic-3918//p=8d0d242ba1c94e2889fdc06d90b2c52d","tags":{"__document_id":["origam-topic-3918"],"__file_type":["text/plain"],"__file_id":["cfbae9884f68449e8b129bed1a2d19ab"],"__file_part":["677cb4232735484d8e59274df8a41248"],"__part_n":["0"],"__sect_n":["0"],"source":["origam-community"],"topicId":["3918"],"categoryId":["61"],"url":["https://community.origam.com/t/how-to-view-the-application-database/3918"],"title":["How to view the application database"],"imagesFound":["9"],"imagesDescribed":["9"],"imageUrl":["https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/f/ffcafb0db0169ba5b189e822e850b6a2e3eae3f9.png","https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/c/c30f912394921f448d878ae5dfbb110107086201.png","https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/4/431df366e549099d584959cb9434b24c9a551d59.png","https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/2/2760c5fa61e269064969f35f2202384cc5880d09.png","https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/a/a6ac0c76ff83854782d58d30cc5b657780457273.png","https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/e/e8a96e11f618785fe6f356df4c4a3621d434c125.png","https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/e/ecb02e9ecbdd91579d43283f03e8c0e9033f6f2c.png","https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/9/9c6c0b3449bf9820432a81c273e4b47f5e85c144.png","https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/5/5aa8a69461b9ab676b9cc1b183cffb25b49c4b2e.png"]},"payload":{"url":"","schema":"20231218A","file":"content.txt","text":"# How to view the application database\n\nURL: https://community.origam.com/t/how-to-view-the-application-database/3918\n\n@vikter (2025-01-23 08:41:21Z):\n   \n This article will show you how you can view the contents of a database that runs under any application created in the ORIGAM platform. \n \n [!success]- Prerequisites for further work \nThere are two basic prerequisites you need to meet: \n \n  Have a running database server  \n  Have a project created in ORIGAM Architect  \n \n \n   Database tool \n If you meet these conditions, then you just need to have any of the database viewing tools installed on your computer. \n Here we will use Azure Data Studio, which is multiplatform (for Windows, MacOS, and Linux), multidatabase (MS SQL, PostgreSQL, \u2026), free to use, and available to download at this  link . \n UPDATE: Azure Data Studio retired in FEB 2026 and was replaced by  Visual Studio Code . \nIn case you plan to use only PostgreSQL databases, you may use  pgAdmin  or you can see some other alternatives  below . \n You can, of course, use any other tool of your choice that can display the contents of an MS SQL database, of which there are many available. \n Once you have a tool, you can move on. \n   Viewing your database \n The first step is to configure the connection to your database (DB) server. \n In Azure Data Studio, it is easy\u2014you just create a  New connection : \n  \n\n\n[Image: https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/f/ffcafb0db0169ba5b189e822e850b6a2e3eae3f9.png]\nDescription: The image displays the welcome screen of Azure Data Studio, a data management tool. The prominent title \u0022Azure Data Studio\u0022 is centrally located, accompanied by a set of options including \u0022New,\u0022 \u0022Open file...,\u0022 and \u0022Open folder...\u0022. A dropdown menu under \u0022New\u0022 lists various options: \u0022New connection,\u0022 \u0022New query\u0022 with the shortcut \u0022Ctrl\u002BN,\u0022 \u0022New notebook\u0022 with the shortcut \u0022Alt\u002BWindows\u002BN,\u0022 and \u0022Deploy a server.\u0022 The interface features a blue color scheme with graphical elements representing data and operations. The overall purpose is to facilitate data-related tasks such as querying and connecting to data sources.\n\n\n  \n Now fill in the connection details. That may look, for example, like this: \n  \n\n\n[Image: https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/c/c30f912394921f448d878ae5dfbb110107086201.png]\nDescription: The image displays a \u0022Connection Details\u0022 dialog for connecting to a Microsoft SQL Server database. The interface includes fields for \u0022Connection type,\u0022 which is set to \u0022Microsoft SQL Server,\u0022 and \u0022Input type,\u0022 with the option selected as \u0022Parameters.\u0022 The \u0022Server\u0022 field is filled with \u0022localhost,\u0022 and the \u0022Authentication type\u0022 is set to \u0022SQL Login.\u0022 Other fields include \u0022User name\u0022 marked as \u0022sa,\u0022 a password field represented with asterisks, and a checkbox labeled \u0022Remember password.\u0022 The \u0022Database\u0022 field is set to \u0022myapplication,\u0022 and options for \u0022Encrypt,\u0022 \u0022Trust server certificate,\u0022 and \u0022Server group\u0022 are visible, with the group set to \u0022\u003CDefault\u003E.\u0022 An optional \u0022Name\u0022 field is indicated with \u0022MS SQL 2022 DB server.\u0022 The dialog features a \u0022Connect\u0022 button at the bottom, along with an \u0022Advanced...\u0022 button for additional settings. The purpose of this dialog is to facilitate the configuration of a connection to an SQL Server database.\n\n\n  \n Just a couple of notes on the connection configuration: \n \n Connection type: We are using MS SQL here, but you can use PostgreSQL as well. \n Server: We assume here you are running the database locally, but you can, of course, use any available and accessible DB server. \n User name and password: You entered that in the database connection setup while creating your database server in Docker using the script described  here . \n Database: Here we have selected the specific database we want to connect to ( myapplication ), but if you want to see all existing databases of your projects, do not fill in the database name in the connection settings. \n Name: This is just the name of the connection you will see in Azure Data Studio. \n \n If your database server is up and running and your username and password are correct, you will connect to your database and see the following tables: \n  \n\n\n[Image: https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/4/431df366e549099d584959cb9434b24c9a551d59.","vector_provider":"AI.Ollama.OllamaTextEmbeddingGenerator","vector_generator":"__","last_update":"2026-05-01T23:41:52"},"vector":[0.02660433,-0.018471645,-0.061043315,0.029459778,-0.011170527,-0.055784825,0.009366282,-0.02568969,0.0015992841,0.0041892277,0.009525173,-0.033151723,-0.0013124592,0.023594007,0.031142041,0.0218607,-0.0015013607,0.01705482,0.01960941,0.041564684,0.005297614,0.0125368545,0.069287844,-0.0014593267,-0.0038466065,-0.015333187,-0.04395157,-0.014018137,0.025683925,-0.008261074,0.009529297,-0.04490162,0.007103628,-0.022983214,-0.016480472,-0.0091044195,0.033521168,-0.017255414,-0.04006582,0.04028794,0.017028939,-0.027245764,-0.030839402,0.028116757,0.029066978,-0.025457697,-0.021420643,-0.006838616,0.011049416,-0.005814269,-0.03568518,-0.031710267,0.027448976,-0.026846327,0.045169927,0.025411794,-0.016082453,-0.0020239316,-0.07215354,0.006022207,-0.035463713,0.017925896,-0.028119924,-0.009615954,0.0058119944,0.03788346,-0.02307034,-0.025714967,-0.019277219,-0.017668553,0.00627138,0.021585833,-0.05854636,-0.014527198,-0.071057096,-0.004184627,0.039053194,0.013868267,-0.035842936,-0.018151684,-0.020839972,-0.0034798996,0.0050585777,-0.0063285297,-0.043848667,-0.0010850219,-0.013696825,0.089826,0.022284474,0.07241822,0.024589501,-0.028580302,0.063718766,-0.010432414,-0.027265925,-0.027148146,0.014601943,0.012532257,0.046148516,0.01893357,-0.04486587,-0.057865843,-0.01475564,0.01811724,-0.039799746,-0.0043901782,-0.0034793457,-0.011233546,0.00148514,-0.03325997,-0.015073162,-0.015061603,0.06496298,-0.031433288,0.0113736335,-0.006474133,-0.018203637,-0.027138064,-0.01172193,0.021161864,0.007872148,0.032904904,0.032785304,-0.010195353,0.0028137139,0.013984373,0.007072612,0.02191316